NORMALISED EXTRACT
Enabling ESM in Node.js
- Methods to mark module as ES module:
  - Use .mjs file extension.
  - Set package.json "type" field to "module" for .js files.
  - Use --input-type=module CLI flag for one-off scripts.

Import specifiers and resolution
- Specifier types: relative (./file.js), bare (package-name), absolute (file:///path).
- Relative and absolute specifiers require explicit file extensions; directory indexes must be fully specified with file name and extension.
- Bare specifiers are resolved via Node.js package resolution algorithm; packages with "exports" restrict internal file access to declared export paths.
- file:, node:, data: URL schemes supported; file URL imports must have percent-encoding for special characters.

import.meta features
- import.meta.url: absolute file: URL of current module.
- import.meta.filename: full absolute path with symlinks resolved (file: modules only).
- import.meta.dirname: directory name of current module (same as path.dirname(import.meta.filename)).
- import.meta.main: boolean true if module is entry point of process; analogous to require.main === module.
- import.meta.resolve(specifier) -> returns resolved absolute URL string synchronously; caveats: may perform sync filesystem ops and not available in custom loaders without experimental flag.

CommonJS interoperability
- Importing CJS from ESM: module.exports is provided as default export; static analysis attempts to surface named exports on the namespace object.
- Default import forms: import cjs from './cjs.cjs' yields cjs === module.exports.
- createRequire(module.createRequire()) can be used within ESM to construct require when necessary.
- Named export detection is heuristic and not guaranteed to reflect dynamic changes to module.exports at runtime.

File extension and URL rules
- Mandatory file extensions for import statements resolving relative/absolute specifiers.
- Data URL imports supported for specific MIME types: text/javascript (ESM), application/json (JSON), application/wasm (Wasm). JSON imports require import with { type: 'json' } attribute.

SUPPLEMENTARY DETAILS
Best practices
- Prefer explicit file extensions in import statements for portability between Node and browser environments.
- Use import.meta.url with URL/file utilities to load relative assets: new URL('./data.proto', import.meta.url).
- When mixing CJS and ESM, prefer default import and avoid relying on heuristic named exports.

